# What I (Still) Love About the Web

I'm new here to the SmolNet (~2 weeks), but instantly fell in love with it. In particular, my feelings of revulsion for the web had been rapidly compounding for the preceding several months (years, actually—but the preceding months the rate was increasing exponentially, or so it's felt).

Sick of the ads, sick of the constant “Hey, Listen!” of underhanded and (intended to be) subtle techniques for “fooling” me into spending a bit of my time and mental energy looking at something I wouldn't have chosen to look at if it were candid about what it is. Sick of having to learn new skills just to avoid the latest such traps.

Sick of being lured into convenient platforms, becoming dependent upon them, and then watching with dismay as, once the VCs decide it's time to stop trying to catch fire, and time to start making a return on their investment, the websites become abysmally less permissive, more restrictive, more greedy, prevent you from linking to content that might direct the flow of traffic to other platforms/other advertisers, weaken their feed “algorithms” to make it harder to find what you're actually even there for, so you spend more time floundering around amongst their ads.

It happened with Pinterest, Facebook, it happened with the Google search platform, it happened with YouTube, it happened with GMail, it happened with Meetup... boy oh boy did it happen with Twitter/X! I haven't felt it as keenly (though some have) on Google Workspace, Discord, or GitHub... but at this point the pattern is abundantly clear: either use decentralized, self-hostable services and protocols, or fall prey to another trap.

And I mean, some of this I still genuinely can't escape. For social media/connection with my communities, fortunately there's Blusky/the AT protocol, and there's Mastodon, and those serve just fine. I still have some ties to Facebook, but I'll be extricating myself soon enough. (It's just a pity that some of the most-vibrant communities for my beloved retro computing platforms are still hosted there.)

But many of the centralized platforms on which I rely, have no viable alternatives (for my personal needs). All the independently-created video content I care to see is on YouTube alone, with barely an exception or two, and indeed it would be extremely difficult for someone without their resources, to put together a similarly-reliable video delivery platform. If I invest in some serious hard disk space, I could choose to put my own content on a home server or somesuch (and watch it crash to the ground if any of that content were to become even mildly popular)—but I'm not much of a content creator, I'm very much a consumer. And I'm not seeing the creators of my consumed content putting up private servers or taking part in any decentralized YouTube-alike. So the choice is to keep myself entrapped (until things become intolerable), or rob myself of a significant chunk of things that I genuinely enjoy.

For Google Workspace, for many people there really is no viable alternative (...yet). Euro Office just released their 1.0, and there are some platforms based upon it, and that's great to see for a number of reasons. But it has a long way to go before it's a reasonable replacement for Workspace or MS Office, for most peopl. (For myself, I can probably migrate an awful lot of it to a self-hosted HedgeDocs, combined with alternative cloud storage, so I'm going to work on 
